      "writtenOn": "2016-08-05T00:06:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It seems like we\u0027re using a number of different terms here for the same concept: the counter values used by a timeline.  (I\u0027m assuming that \"pt\" is a timeline counter value.  Actually, in some documentation on opengl fences I saw in reading up on this [http://www.linuxplumbersconf.net/2014/ocw//system/presentations/2355/original/03%20-%20sync%20\u0026%20dma-fence.pdf, the slide on \u0027Sync -- after merge\u0027], \"timeline point\" seemed to be used used for an object type containing the \u003ctimeline_id, counter_value\u003e pair, with the restriction that a timeline point is unique to a given fence -- so if two fences wanted to reference the same pair, they couldn\u0027t share the timeline point object.  If that usage is widespread, then using \"timeline point\" as the name of the pair might be a little misleading.)  Elsewhere we refer to:\n* \"monotonically increasing counter\"\n* \"timeline numbers\"\n\" \"timeline counters\"\nI would advise treating this spec a little more mathematically -- defining one term, and using it strictly.\n\nHow about we talk about a timeline having a counter, and that having counter values.  A fence (in this restricted form where there\u0027s only a single timeline) consists of a timeline reference and a \"target counter value\".  Sound reasonable?\n\nFeel free to push back with alternate names.  But I would like to see the terminology more consistent and precise, whatever the choice of terms is.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 80,
        "startChar": 3,
        "endLine": 80,
        "endChar": 17
      },
      "revId": "aa8036617e4eeb4617ac056673d20ec6644d29f4",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d4762e83_a4866cbe",
        "filename": "android/emulation/goldfish_sync.h",
        "patchSetId": 68
      },
      "lineNbr": 84,
